{
  "answer": "In Viṣṇu Smṛti, Chapter 5 details punishments (*daṇḍa*) for offenses, including the \"great sins\" (*mahāpātakas*), one of which is theft.[^1] For a person of low *varṇa* (i.e., anyone except a Brahmin), theft as a *mahāpātaka* incurs the death penalty.[^2] By contrast, a Brahmin offender receives no corporal punishment but is instead branded (specifically, with the mark of a dog's foot for theft) and banished from the country.[^3][^4]\n\n**Comparison of scaling**: The text explicitly exempts Brahmins from execution or physical mutilation for even the gravest offenses, substituting symbolic branding and exile—a stark disparity reflecting *varṇa*-based hierarchy. Lesser thefts (e.g., of specific goods below *mahāpātaka* thresholds) receive fines or amputations without explicit *varṇa* differentiation, but the king is advised to scale punishments by caste (*varṇa*), wealth, and age in such cases.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, [Chapter 5/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, [Chapter 5/translation/#p-2c7e24](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-2c7e24).\n\n[^3]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, [Chapter 5/translation/#p-8c285b](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-8c285b); [Chapter 5/translation/#p-583b27](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-583b27).\n\n[^4]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, [Chapter 5/translation/#p-8d4644](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-8d4644).\n\n[^5]: Viṣṇu Smṛti, [Chapter 5/translation/#p-f76990](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-f76990).",
